The '''First Map of ''The Lord of the Rings''''' refers to the earliest map of the western regions of Middle-earth that was drawn by [[J.R.R. Tolkien]].<ref>{{TI|Map}}, p. 295</ref> The map has squares of 2 centimetre side and a map scale where 2 centimetres are the equivalent of 100 miles.<ref>{{TI|Redrawn}}, last paragraph on p. 300</ref> It was redrawn and commented on by [[Christopher Tolkien]] in ''[[The Treason of Isengard]]'' (1989; chapter 15).<ref>{{TI|Redrawn}}, pp. 301 to 321</ref> 

The First Map of the Lord of the Rings covers a larger area of Middle-earth than the [[General Map of Middle-earth]] or [[The West of Middle-earth at the End of the Third Age]] map. It also shows the lands to the north of the [[Icebay of Forochel]] and the island of [[Tol Fuin]] west of the island of [[Himling]] off the coast of [[Forlindon]] in the [[Belegaer]] ocean. The sea west of the [[Icebay of Forochel]] was labeled as ''[[North Sea]]'' in pencil.
==Early concepts==
A label "Forodwaith (Northerland)" is written in the area between the river [[Baranduin]] and the river [[Gwathló]] and extends from south of the [[Sarn Ford]] to beyond the northern end of the [[Misty Mountains]]. There is no label "Eriador" on the map. However, J.R.R. Tolkien added "(or Eriador)" after "Forodwaith" on The 1943 Map of The Lord of the Rings.<ref>{{TI|MII}}, p. 306</ref> This and the absence of the name Eriador from earlier manuscripts suggest that Forodwaith was initially used as a name of the region that was later called Eriador.

A label "[[Westfold]]" was written to the south of a label "[[Dunland]]" west of the southern end of the Misty Mountains and north of the river [[Isen]], but was struck through<ref>{{TI|MIVd}}, p. 320</ref> and reinserted west of [[Edoras]], north of the northern foothills of the [[White Mountains|"Black Mountains"]].<ref>{{WR|1|II}}, Notes, Note 4, pp. 22-23</ref> This and the use of the name Westfold for the land of the Westfolders, the invaders of Rohan in earlier drafts of ''[[The Two Towers]]''<ref>{{WR|1|II}}, pp. 21-22</ref><ref>{{WR|1|III}}, Notes, Note 8, p. 41</ref> suggest that Westfold was initially used as a name of the region that was later called Dunland.
